		<div class="comment-author vcard">
			<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/f22a7184111ed1d9ef5f22e3c90c5089?s=40&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D40&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-40 photo' height='40' width='40' />			<cite class="fn">Steve</cite> <span class="says">says:</span>		</div><!-- .comment-author .vcard -->
		
		<div class="comment-meta commentmetadata"><a href="http://blogs.standard.net/the-political-surf/2013/10/28/mormons-catholics-both-deal-with-dark-side-of-their-histories/#comment-45879">
			October 28, 2013 at 4:52 pm</a>		</div><!-- .comment-meta .commentmetadata -->

		<div class="comment-body"><p>In the mid-90s I glanced at my mother&#8217;s Relief Society manual (or maybe Home Teaching manual, I can&#8217;t remember which) and it stated that at the Mountain Meadow Massacre the Mormons only shot the men, while the Indians shot the women and children. I was so stunned by this that I had to read it several times to convince myself it actually said that. I wondered then (and still do) if anyone actually believed that crap.</p>
<p>So as late as the mid-1990s Native Americans were being scapegoated for the atrocities at Mountain Meadow by the Mormon church, and according to an official church manual killing men was just fine. This is the kind of moral Twister you end up playing when you&#8217;re unwilling to acknowledge anything bad in your past.</p>
</div>

